<Docs title="Cleave Orchestrator" description="Parallel task execution via git worktrees with automatic merge, conflict detection, and adversarial review.">
  <h1>Cleave Orchestrator</h1>
  <p>
    Cleave decomposes complex tasks into independent subtasks and executes them in parallel
    across isolated git worktree branches. Each child runs in its own worktree with its own
    branch, and results are merged back with conflict detection.
  </p>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Assess</strong> — <code>cleave_assess</code> evaluates task complexity (systems × modifiers). If score ≥ 2.0, recommends decomposition.</li>
    <li><strong>Plan</strong> — the agent creates a split plan: children with labels, descriptions, file scopes, and dependency ordering.</li>
    <li><strong>Execute</strong> — <code>cleave_run</code> creates git worktrees, dispatches child processes in parallel (up to 4 by default), and monitors progress.</li>
    <li><strong>Merge</strong> — completed children are merged back to the parent branch. Conflicts are detected per-file (never bulk-resolved).</li>
    <li><strong>Review</strong> — optional adversarial review loop checks for bugs, security issues, and spec compliance.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Usage</h2>
  <pre><code># The agent suggests cleave when complexity is high:
"Implement the provider routing engine with routing.rs, ollama.rs, and per-child cleave config"
# Agent: cleave_assess → complexity 3.0 → recommends decomposition

# Or trigger explicitly:
/cleave</code></pre>

  <h2>With OpenSpec</h2>
  <p>
    When an OpenSpec change exists (from <code>design_tree_update(implement)</code>), cleave
    integrates with the spec lifecycle:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Child tasks receive design context from <code>design.md</code></li>
    <li><code>tasks.md</code> is reconciled after merge — marking completed tasks</li>
    <li>Post-merge: <code>/assess spec</code> verifies specs are satisfied</li>
    <li>Then <code>/opsx:archive</code> closes the change</li>
  </ul>
  <pre><code># Full lifecycle:
# 1. design_tree_update(implement) on a decided node
# 2. /opsx:ff generates tasks
# 3. /cleave executes in parallel
# 4. /assess spec verifies
# 5. /opsx:archive closes</code></pre>

  <h2>Complexity Formula</h2>
  <p>
    <code>complexity = systems × (1 + 0.5 × modifiers)</code>
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Systems</strong> — distinct subsystems touched (files, modules, layers)</li>
    <li><strong>Modifiers</strong> — data migration, breaking changes, cross-cutting concerns</li>
    <li><strong>Threshold</strong> — default 2.0; below this, execute directly</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Child Isolation</h2>
  <p>
    Each child runs in a separate git worktree on its own branch. This means:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Children cannot interfere with each other's working trees</li>
    <li>Each child sees the same starting state (parent branch HEAD)</li>
    <li>File scope declarations prevent children from touching the same files</li>
    <li>Merge order respects declared dependencies between children</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Adversarial Review</h2>
  <p>
    Enable with <code>review: true</code> in cleave_run. After each child completes, a
    reviewer checks for:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Bugs and logic errors</li>
    <li>Security issues (injection, path traversal, unsafe patterns)</li>
    <li>Spec compliance (if OpenSpec change is bound)</li>
    <li>Churn detection — if the same issues reappear after fixes, bail</li>
  </ul>
</Docs>
